folder: Roosevelt Avenue & Main Street, Queens, NY
text:
Roosevelt Avenue, south side, between Main and Union Streets, showing the Flushing Institute. The institute grounds at one time occupied the entire block from Main to Union Streets and was bounded on the south by the Long Island Railroad tracks.
View 2 shows the extension wing of the Institute; and view 3 the site after the buildings were razed.
Views 1,2: 1922
View 3: 1925
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

folder: Roosevelt Avenue & Main Street, Queens, NY
text:
Roosevelt Avenue, north side, east from near Main Street, showing two old frame houses with stuccoed fronts, the Consolidated Edison Company Building, No. 136-21, and the tower of the First Methodist Episcopal Church of Flushing.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  June, 1925
2) A view of the second of the two old dwellings seen in view 1. The first of the two was demolished when a 6-story office building, housing the Bank of Manhattan, was erected on the
site.
P.L.Sperr  August 21, 1935
3) Viewing westward on Roosevelt Avenue, from near the Consolidated Edison Building. The building occupies the site of the A.L. Fitch house. Views 1 and 3 show also subway construction operations.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  June, 1925

folder: Roosevelt Avenue & Main Street (East)., Queens, NY
text:
Roosevelt Avenue, east from Main Street. View 2 shows the north side of the avenue at Main Street, viewing east across the latter. The office building, which houses the Bank of Manhattan,
is at the N. E. corner of the two thoroughfares.
View 3 shows the buildings on the south side of the avenue, looking east from Main Street. The Flushing Institute formerly stood here.
View 1:  October 11, 1930
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
Views 2,3:  August 24, 1935
P. L. Sper
